The Federal Government said it would soon commission the already completed 40 megawatts (MW) Kashimbilla hydropower plant, the Takum, Wukari transmission substations in Taraba state and other projects to boost national electricity grid. Engr. Sale Mamman, Minister of Power, confirmed this at the weekend during an inspection tour to the plant along with the Minister of State, Mr. Goddy Agba and other dignitaries. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network Engr Ali-Dapshima Abubakar, Project Manager in the Ministry of Power, who conducted them around the project sites said the Kashimbilla Hydropower was upgraded from 6MW to 40MW. He said the dam and the hydropower components were completed since October 17, 2017; the evacuation project was at 90 per cent level in June, 2019 and would be ready for power generation soon. The dam would check flood threats from Lake Nyos located along the Cameroon line of volcanic activity, while providing power. It would also provide water supply to about 400,000 people and boost irrigation for agriculture. At the Takum 2x60MVA, 132/33kV substation, Engr. Abubakar said the Wukari, Takun and Kashimbilla power projects were 100% completed and ready to energise. Mamman expressed satisfaction on the projects and assured of addressing challenges to ensure they are energized. Mr. Usman Gur, the Managing Director of the Transmission Company of Nigeria (TCN) said he was satisfied with the substationâ€™s work. Briefing the ministers, he said when power was evacuated from the plant; it would serve the Northeast, North-Central and the Southeast.